enominationalism with the split between Traditionalism and Reform, the threat of antisemitism, the origins of American Zionism, and interreligious dialogue. The book concludes with a chapter on the professionalization of the rabbinate and the legacy bequeathed to the next century. On all those key issues rabbis spoke out individually or in debates with other rabbis. From the evidence presented, the congregational rabbi emerges as a pioneer, the leader of a congregation, as well as spokesman for the Jews in the larger society, forging an independence from his European counterparts, and laboring for the preservation of the Jewish faith and heritage in an unfamiliar environment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aJewish sermons, AmericanxHistory and criticism. 0aJewszUnited StatesxIdentity. 0aJewszUnited StatesxSocial conditionsy19th century. 0aJudaismzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aRabbiszUnited StatesxOfficexHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh  a1900.  aBased.  aJewish.  aReformers.  aTraditionalists.  abeen.  abefore.  aboth.  acommunity.  aengaged.  ahave.  aheretofore.  ahost.  alargely.  amatters.  aneglected.  aother.  apublic.  arabbis.  asermons.  asources.  astatements.  athat.  atraces.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814772942423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814772942/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  a